A picture of the legal status of bitcoin around the world.
Summary: In addition to price reversals naturally triggered by speculative attributes, the sharp decline in the current round of digital currencies is not unrelated to the “hostile” - regulatory risk.
Viewable maps show that Eastern countries are more conservative than the West in their bitcoin approach, that countries that dominate the world are still watching digital currency legitimacy, and that the “black swan risk” remains high.
* This paper is from Wall Street News (Wind:wallstreamcn), editor Wang Mu. More wonderful information can be found on the Wallstreamcn.com or on Wall Street. ♪ I'm sorry ♪
With the storm of regulation in major markets such as China, South Korea and the European Union, the global digital currency, headed by Bitcoin, has been bloody since this week, with Bitcoin prices falling by $10,000 a week, the largest single-day decline in three years.
In addition to the price reversals naturally triggered by speculative attributes, the sharp decline in the current round of digital currencies is not unrelated to the long-standing “hostile” — regulatory risk.
At this important juncture, the visualized big data site HowMuch.net produced a map showing the legitimacy and regulatory level of bitcoin in countries around the globe.
As the figure below shows, green represents the legitimate market for bitcoin; orange represents the neutral market, which has not yet publicly legalized its status, but has no major use restrictions; light pink represents the restricted market, where local governments try to use the digital currency through red-line policies or regulation; dark pink represents the country where bitcoin is defined as illegal; and grey is an unapproved country.
(The above figure is from the HowMuch.Net visualization team at the 15th of January.)
According to the article, the distribution of the green pieces in Central Africa shows that the traditional Eastern countries are more conservative than the West in their bitcoin attitude.
Russia is currently the largest country to have outlawed bitcoin, China is one of the largest restricted markets for bitcoin, and India is one of the largest countries to have no comment on the bitcoin and no relevant policy.
North America and Western Europe are the regions with the highest acceptance of bitcoin, i.e., the distribution of green blocks is more concentrated.
The views of the countries of the Middle East and Latin America in the form of a relatively different currency are evident, with a more mixed distribution of the colours in the above-mentioned regions.
Among them, Iraq, Iran, Turkey, Brazil are legitimate bitcoin markets, Afghanistan, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Egypt, Bolivia, etc. have some restrictions on their trade and use, and more Latin American countries have yet to speak out.
A synthesis of the above-mentioned data shows that 99 countries (or 40 per cent) of the 246 countries surveyed globally have no restrictions on trade in and use of bitcoin, i.e. green and orange areas.
7 countries (or 3 per cent) are restricted markets (light pink) and 10 countries (or 4 per cent) TTs are illegal (deep pink), and 130 countries (or 53 per cent) do not yet have more treatment for digital currency information (grey).
This suggests that the countries that make up the global majority (53 per cent, more than half) are still waiting for the domestic legitimacy of the digital currency headed by Bitcoin, and that the “black swan risk” of Bitcoin remains high, as some of these countries may eventually take legislative decisions to restrict the monetary currency.
According to the article, the emerging category of digital currency is not fully understood by global regulators and may be the main reason that most countries have not yet made a declaration.
Although Bitcoin's “human gas” has grown exponentially since last year, it does not represent an interest for all countries, and it may be that some countries are concerned about the consequent threat to local French currency or are more concerned about the use of digital currency by criminal organizations.
Wall Street News has written a detailed summary of international regulatory news about Bitcoin since last week, including China’s launch of a centralized service online platform and mobile App for off-site exchanges, South Korea’s continuing consideration of the closure of a digital currency exchange, and the EU’s belief that Bitcoin is not widely accepted and warns investors of the risk of “loss of their blood”.
Wall Street editor-in-chief, "Reading Queens 2018: Global Mothers Started the Year of Digital Currency?" It was mentioned that 2018 would be a digital currency year for global central banks from either point of view of regulation, acceptance/criticism or adoption.
The criticism of the legitimacy of Bitcoin by large countries such as Russia is in fact intended to give way to the official issuance of digital currency.
