Block the critics on Facebook: If you can't stand the voters' blame, don't run for office.
Our father knows bad media.
American people loved Washington, but shortly thereafter, major newspapers began to vehemently criticize him for everything, from domestic policy to political principles.
He was angry with these criticisms, without doubt.
But he did not silence those critics.
For as early as 1783, Washington said, “freedom of speech is denied — we will be slaughtered like lambs in silence and ignorance”.
This reminds me of Larry Hogan, Governor of Maryland, who needs to learn from Washington.
Hogan's staff blocked and deleted at least 450 posts because they expressed their views on his Facebook official home page.
The American Civil Liberties Union brought proceedings against him in this regard earlier this week.
The governor's staff considered the lawsuit to be hasty, and online coverage was full of their strong resistance: “Who cares?”
Many people say, "It's just Facebook."
But it's important.
This is particularly important because it is faced with people like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor in a democratic majority state, and he is surprisingly popular.
Of the 50 governors in the country, he received the second best rating.
Hogan is not a reactionary impatient.
He took control of Maryland and strictly observed the rules.
He was also very good at using Facebook as the main means of reaching out to voters, and showed the baldness of his chemotherapy for the first time on his home page.
So those who blocked comments on the Governor's home page were completely unnecessary and ultimately dangerous. The home page is a public forum and an official management platform for public tax-supporting employees.
In an interview with the Washington Post, Hogan ' s spokesman, Amelia Shass, defended the Governor ' s behaviour by saying that she believed that blocking their comments was merely an attempt to restrain them.
But they were too hasty to describe it as a flood beast or a cynical cynic across the network.
The Washington Post spoke face-to-face with someone who had been shielded by Hogan.
They are just ordinary people talking to their elected leaders: They are teachers, small business owners and priests, not flood beasts.
They say that their comments are deep, respectful and not indecent.
The priest quoted the Bible in his post and called on Hogan to remember his Catholic faith.
Lakshmi Salma Ramani, lawyer in Boy, Maryland, was not cynical, but asked about hate crimes.
She wrote in the news story section of The Washington Post, “I am polite to comment that I am disappointed that he did not respond to hate crimes and other recent news events.
I also do not like a group of people commenting on the same subject, because they are simply ignored by people who think they are so-called public minds, not citizens of a country that worries.”
The so-called “intensive garbage-information bombing” by the governor's staff may seem to others to be a “continuing claim”.
The Facebook era has made it easy to modify a message by shielding a critic or deleting a negative comment.
It was also much cleaner than in the past, when it was necessary to send staff to collect and burn newspapers with critical statements or to arrest or silence protesters.
But that is what is happening now, just at the digital level.
Hogan is not the first public official to be blamed for scolding others on Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being prosecuted by Twitter users for blocking them on Twitter.
Last week, a landmark ruling was made in Virginia on such issues.
According to James Cacharis, District Judge of Alexandria, United States of America, the Chairman of the Lauden County Supervisory Committee blocked voters from her Facebook page in violation of the First Amendment.
The Governor of Kentucky, Matt Bevin (R), was also visited by the American Civil Liberties Union for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be so hard.
In the Washington era, affordable postage and the Internet had a similar impact.
The number of newspapers in the press quadrupled between 1776 and 1800, with anonymous letters strongly criticizing his leadership.
And even then, Washington had an anonymous flood beast against him.
People used pseudonyms such as Yurikla, Valerius, Belisalu, and Pagos to write to the press to harshly criticize Washington’s decision-making.
According to historical documents collected by George Washington newspaper's online project, his office was flooded with petitions criticizing his attitude on the Treaty of Friendship, Commerce and Navigation between His Majesty the British King and the United States of America, signed with Britain.
But he didn't silence them.
Freedom of expression, dissent and speech are the foundations of the country.
And true leaders need to accept that.
