16-year-old Julianus Yemmer was unconscious as a result of severe beatings.
A few hours later, a fire broke out in the nearby government agency Election Commission building, which escalated the following day.
About 1,000 young Papuan men, women and children gathered at a football field in front of local police stations and military command centres to demand justice.
With their ceremonial hunting bows, they danced the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua -- running in circles and imitating birds.
Some protesters started throwing stones at regular military posts.
According to an official document read in Time magazine, when emotions continue to intensify, soldiers receive orders from their internal radios: “If the crowd resists more than three times, the execution is imminent”. However, this document was not released to the local media.
Jeremias Kayamu, 56 years old, who was the head of the Enarotali Kego Koto neighbourhood, felt threatened and appealed to the crowd to calm down and beg them to come home.
But no one is in the mood to listen to him.
He stood on the porch of his colorful cabin and told Time magazine, "When I turned back, my left wrist was shot."
Kayaki still does not know who fired the gun, but he says the bullet came from among the soldiers who gathered.
And he said, "It was crowded and they fired a lot of shots."
According to the cousin of the local Olfius Juul, he witnessed the shooting and saw Olfius Juul being shot three times.
Juhanes sadly told Time magazine, "I ran to check his body to see if it was him.
