The Moor Beach Tragic: A return to racist lynching and justice for activists
In 1948, a Ford Mercury car came through a crowd of viewers in the town of Monroe, Georgia, running towards the tiny Moor Beach Bridge.
The vehicle, carrying four black passengers and one white driver, was blocked by a group of white men with guns before it reached the bridge.
The mob leader-- a middle-aged man in a striped suit-- takes a deep sip of cigars, eyes in the windshield.
The passengers in the car were full of fear.
"We want-Roger!" The man shouted.
"Get him out of the car!"
A young black man was dragged down from an ex-passenger seat and screamed into silence.
Fortunately, July 22nd, this terrible scene was just a repeat.
But when Roger's neck was covered with a cord, almost all the viewers made a real gasp.
Since 2005, civil rights activists returned to the Moor Beach Bridge, where two black couples - Roger and Dorothy Malcolm and George and Merey Dossy - were hanged in 1946 by the three K parties.
No one has ever been charged with murder.
“Although we know who they are, and although we have seen them in the community, it is incredible that none of them has been arrested over the years” Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize this recurrence, said.
“This is a stain on history and a burden on our souls.”
Brooks, 71 years old, was a former Georgia congressman and a lifetime defender.
For him, the repetition was a dramatic call that reminded the people of the Monroe community every year that injustice had never been corrected.
“We want to sue, we want to close, we want to heal, we want reconciliation, but we must first get justice”, he said.
“We will not be cured and reconciled unless we have justice.”
On July 27, 1946, the Coroner placed a bed sheet on the body of a lynching victim at Moore Beach.
According to FBI files obtained by the National Broadcasting Corporation News, more than 50 men from Monroe and surrounding counties are suspected of involvement in lynchings.
None of them has been prosecuted.
Although suspects have been at large for decades, civil rights activists have indicated that the dual motive for lynching is well known throughout the town: political and sexual.
In April 1946, a Supreme Court ruling enabled black citizens of Georgia to vote in the initial elections for the first time later in the summer.
According to the FBI, at about the same time, the black tenant Roger Malcolm assassinated the white landlord, Bannet Hearst, in a struggle that looked like it was for a woman.
According to Brooks, the rumor in town was that Herst slept with Malcolm's wife, Dorothy, and her baby was not her husband's.
According to the FBI, on 25 July 1946, a prominent white landlord, Roy Harrison, spent $600 bailing Malcolm out of prison.
Dorothy and cousins McMerry and George Dorsey accompanied him to prison.
However, when they returned from prison to the Moor Beach Bridge, a group of vigilantes surrounded the car.
“It turns out that Harrison organized and ordered the murder”, an FBI report concluded.
“It is clear that there is a conspiracy between state and local law enforcement authorities, who not only participated in the murder, destroyed evidence, but also concealed the identity of witnesses.”
Brooks is very brief.
He said, “This is a vote tragedy”.
“They were killed by the murderer who sent a message to the black people in the community: `If you register and vote, you will suffer the same fate.”
For almost a decade, Cassandra Green has been in charge of leading the annual re-emergence of the Moor Beach lynching.
Her behaviour is well-articulated, distasteful and racist. Many wanted that racism to cease to exist in the United States.
It's hard to see, it's harder not to look, but Green says it's the key.
“We do not want to talk about lynching, because it exposes us to the ugly face of all”, she said.
“But if you don't listen to me, or if you don't hear me tell my story, I can't have a relationship with you.”
This year's show started in June, and on the first day there were almost 30 actors -- a dozen whites, the rest blacks -- sitting in a room, listening to Green's rehearsing show overview.
Wade Malbau was co-director of Green.
He's been playing the Klan for years, but he says it's never easy.
"I feel dirty because I'm not like this," said Malbau.
“But I think it is very important to keep this history alive, because we don't want to go back to that era.”
In the room, the actors Roger Malcolm and Barnetthurst, Darios Bradshaw and Nick Rascona, rehearsed their lines.
At the beginning of the play, Malcolm shouted and pushed Herst away, outraged that he had slept with his wife, Dorothy.
"I said, get out of my land!"
Rascona echoes.
And then they fight.
And then everybody laughs.
Green laughs the best.
"What's wrong?" Lascona asked.
He was scared and confused.
Am I overplaying it?
"No," Green laughs.
"I just don't think white people say, "Aah."
"Yes," another black actor plays funny.
"You must speak hard."
So the energy in the room has changed; the feeling of fraternity has driven away.
Everyone tried to do so not only to perform the play, but also to honour the four victims.
The scene begins again.
This time, when Rascona said the word "aah," it was sharp and powerful.
No one laughs.
Again, the end was strong and swift.
Screams, guns, then silence.
