American media: Chinese Air Force Engineering University scientists research laser satellites for space garbage removal
On January 18, the Reference News Network reported that Chinese scientists had put forward a bold and innovative proposal to use large lasers to clean up a chaotic Earth orbit and destroy old satellites and their sky litter.
According to the United States Newsweek website, on 15 January, researchers from the Chinese Air Force Engineering University prepared a paper entitled " Space-based laser removal small-scale space debris reorbiting model studies " , which described how space debris could be exposed to less hazardous pieces of laser radiation through the use of space-based platform lasers.
It was reported that space debris had been an issue of concern to international space agencies for many years, and NASA had considered options for tracking, detecting and removing man-made debris.
Large-scale space debris is removed through giant networks used to clean and collect waste and by magnets that can be used to suck them out of orbit. Chinese scientists conducted laser simulation studies and concluded that this would be an effective way to clean up Earth orbits.
The summary of the paper states: “(imisto) provides the necessary theoretical basis for the application of space-based platform laser technology for space debris removal.”
A 2014 study by the United States defence giant Lockheed-Martin found that there were approximately 200 threats per day for satellites operating in orbit.
High-speed debris moving along Earth orbit is considered a serious threat to future space missions and is described by ESA experts as “a lethal chain of threats”. High-speed debris has continued to increase over the past year.
It was also reported on 17 January on the United States website for the monthly Mass Machine that space was largely empty, but that space was becoming increasingly crowded near the Earth. Each satellite that we send into space eventually becomes another piece of debris that orbits the Earth and that accumulates over time.
The more debris, the higher the probability that a satellite will be hit by debris, the more it will damage or destroy an investment worth millions of dollars.
Reports indicate that all space agencies have plans to remove space debris in the future.
NASA is considering the use of jet gas to reduce the speed of debris from orbit, Europe is considering launching a satellite with a large web to capture debris and bring it back to Earth, and Japan is thinking of capturing debris with an electric chain.
At the present time, China has also proposed a solution to the problem of space debris, namely, the use of a large laser to crush floating space debris into less harmful pieces.
According to a paper published by a group of researchers at the Chinese Air Force Engineering University in the monthly German newspaper Optical, the installation of such a laser on a satellite would be effective enough to clean up space, at least on the basis of simulation results.
It was reported that the only way to prove effectiveness was to test and that there were currently no arrangements for such missions, but that perhaps sooner or later someone would install lasers on satellites and send them into space.
Once we have done so, we can finally begin to eliminate the problem of space debris once and for all.
