Update on the results of the Swedish age assessment test for asylum-seekers
The latest results of the medical assessment of the age of asylum-seekers in Sweden, using the latest methodology, show that more than 80 per cent of those tested were found to be over 18 years of age, but not all believed in their accuracy.
The Swedish National Centre for Forensic Medicine (R?ttsmediacinalverket) started the test earlier this year.
When it was alleged that the age of some of the refugees claiming to be minors had not been accurately assessed, the Swedish Migration Board (Migrationsverket) designed these tests with a view to conducting a more accurate age assessment during the asylum process.
So far, the Swedish Immigration Service has sent 6880 testers, and the results of a total of 2481 testers between mid-March and 31 July 2017 have been published by the Centre for Forensic Medicine.
Eighty per cent (persons) were convicted of having reached the age of 18 or more, but in 25 other tests, the Swedish National Centre of Forensic Medicine found that the subject “may have reached the age of 18 or more”.
In 432 tests, the result was that the person “may be under 18 years of age”.
Tests are only for people of questionable age.
According to John Graham of the Forensic Medical Centre, these results are consistent with those of previous months.
He told The Local: “These data are not very different from those of previous months, and the figures are very consistent.”
The high proportion of cases in which the age of 18 was determined did not necessarily mean that the asylum-seekers had falsely stated their age.
In May, the Centre published 581 test results and stated that there were 442 “showing that the person was 18 years or older”.
The news newspaper Svenska Dagbladet investigated the results of 581 tests published and found that 243 of them had publicly indicated that they would be 18 years old this year.
An X-ray examination of intellectual teeth and an MRI scan of joints, followed by an analysis by dentists and radiologists, has also been questioned in some areas.
One of the suspects is Claude Marcus, an endocrinologist at Caroline College, whose work includes assessing the biological maturity of people to determine whether they have gone through puberty earlier or later than normal age.
He told the press paper Metro: “I have reason to think so, and I don't think the measurement used should be this way.
The determination of biological age in this way is inaccurate.
If we cannot guarantee accuracy, we should not pretend that we can do it.”
However, Grayson of the Forensic Medicine Centre defended the accuracy of these tests: “It is generally possible to say that there is little risk of determining that a child is an adult”.
The greatest risk is that the person is just under 18 years of age, which is about 10 per cent.
