Following the closure of the High Court of Justice's provision of drug support for NHS, patients will be able to access “changed” HIV prophylaxis from September onwards.
NHS England has announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a drug that can be administered before sexual intercourse, has proven to reduce the risk of infection among at-risk populations by about 86 per cent. Health services will now provide the drug to an estimated 10,000 people through a three-year initial test.
It agreed to fund the experiment after the Court of Appeal had upheld the High Court decision last year. The decision states that, although NHS states that the local authorities should fund the drug, NHS is entitled to pay the costs of the PEP.
The announcement on Thursday was referred to by British CEO NHS Simon Stevens as “a major new intervention”, while the National AIDS Trust (NAT) described it as “a critical moment”.
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be the first registered sexual health clinics. More clinics will join in October, followed by full implementation in England in April 2018.
Pre-exposure Prophylaxis (PREP) is an HIV drug that is administered before sexual intercourse to reduce the risk of HIV infection.
Experiments have shown that PrEP can significantly reduce HIV transmission among populations at risk of infection.
Pre-sexual use means there are enough specific drugs in humans to prevent HIV infection.
It can be taken daily or two hours before sexual intercourse.
Those eligible for treatment include lesbian, bisexual, transgender and HIV-positive persons who have not been successfully treated.
The clinic will determine whether the eligible and agreed participants, including men, women, transgender people and those whose sexual partner has HIV status are unknown for antiretroviral treatment.
Persons residing in England and registered as general practitioners may also enrol in sexual health clinics where they attend.
The scheme will cost £10 million, while the NHS England branch has signed a contract to procure these drugs this week after international competitive procurement.
The experiment aims to assess the full potential of the PEP by collecting clinical evidence on how it is located, absorbed and implemented on the basis of large samples.
Mr. Stevens said: “This major new intervention should complement and reinforce the widespread and growing success of HIV prevention.
This is another milestone in action worth making progress in addressing the major health challenges of humankind over the years.”
“This is the critical moment in the fight against AIDS.
If it does target populations in need and at risk, pre-exposure prophylaxis offer the possibility of changing the British AIDS epidemic.
Starting in September, people at risk of HIV will gain access to an approved new tool through this experiment in England, funded by the NHS, which is truly stand-alone and does not require consultation with sexual partners, which will improve the lives of many people.
We agree with the announcement.”
The CEO of the Terence Higgins Trust, Ian Greene, said: “The first task now is to ensure that the trials move rapidly across the country and that none of those infected with HIV is left behind.
Now we've bought the Prep experimental drugs, and we're ready to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV."
The shadow Minister of Public Health, Sharon Hodgson, stated: “After months of delay and delays by the Government, the start of the prEP first trial was welcome and should have come earlier.
