Under an agreement with his late father, Colin, known by his brother, Paul, as the “principal promoter and dominant figure” of the De Rutis family, owned about two thirds of the company's assets, while Paul accounted for about one third.
According to the documents submitted to the Tribunal, Colin owned $316 million of property, while Paul owned $176 million.
According to Paul, the division of real estate and cash proved to be the crux of the negotiations.
“Colin's proposal for the division of property left him what I thought was best,” he wrote in a first court affidavit in 2015.
Last Friday, after several failures of mediation, the Supreme Court held its first hearing.
Now that the brothers were still fighting for control of the existing business, Paul claimed that Colin had kicked him out.
Colin denied this and accused Paul of poor administration of certain properties.
In the early affidavit submitted by Colin, he expressed the wish to settle the dispute.
“My Italian tradition determines that the family is the most important option. My Italian blood determines that family is the most important thing”, he wrote.
The cost of the case continues to rise, and there are hundreds of pages of affidavits, e-mails and company reports submitted by the top law firms, such as Deloitte, Picher Partners, Charter Cramer, Allan Myers, QC, and senior lawyers hired by both parties.
Both Ms. De Rutis and her late husband, Luigi, were Italian immigrants. They started running popular restaurants and deli stores in the late 1950s and bought a store in Braunrick in the early 1970s.
They used collateral to buy Colin Wood property, where Colin opened the family ' s first jeans shop.
Colin said, "I read in senior year, where he founded Westco, " Paul was little at the time (about 10 years old). "
Anna De Rutis said that she and Luigi, who died in 2012, wanted to give their property to their son in peace.
“Louigi used to say to me that he never wanted the brothers to end up in court”, she wrote.
The other two brothers, Mark and Luke, were no longer members of De Rutis Group, and Colin said that when Mark left, he paid him $10 million and he paid Luke $26 million.
According to Paul, both Luke and Mark “expressed their dissatisfaction with the division of their property clause”.
According to Eddie McGuire, a television star, published in 2015, Colin kept a low profile despite being a member of the former AFL Board.
“Fairfax Media” contacted Colin and Paul and their lawyers on Friday.
But Colin was the only one who replied by text. He stated that since the case had been brought before the Tribunal, “I really cannot say much”.
"My brother Paul chose to sue me and bring our family to court, which is very, very sad," he wrote.
In mid-2016, Colin wrote in a court document that he had tried to meet the demands of his brother.
He said, “Our father does not want to see Paul and I end up in a dispute like this” and added, “He still has hope for its resolution”.
Friday, that hope seems to be dashed.
