In recent times, people have been talking about recent changes in real estate policy. Is the real estate policy coming loose again? Will the diversification of the land policy supply have led to a decline in housing prices?
But when we were worried about real estate prices, about macroeconomic regulation and about future developments in the real estate market, the Daily People's Journal wrote again, and the last time we specifically discussed the regulation of real estate in the Daily People's Journal, the writing of the Daily People's Journal now addresses a much more serious issue than the affordability of housing, even if you can afford it and pay for it.
Today, let's talk about something more serious than buying a house: repayment.
I. China ' s Growing Housing Debt Crisis
According to data from the review article " Awards and Loans: Fighting the pleasures and worries of young people " , published by People ' s Daily Overseas on 17 January, in November 2017, the Third Quarterly Report on China ' s Dilution Process, published by the National Finance and Development Laboratory of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences and the National Balance Sheet Research Centre, indicated that the rate of leverage in the residential sector continued to increase, rising from 47.4 per cent in the second quarter of 2017 to 48.6 per cent in the third quarter, an increase of 1.3 percentage points and 3.8 percentage points in the first three quarters of 2017.
The share of debt of the resident sector in the overall real economy has increased, and the leverage rate has increased faster.
Studies have shown that Chinese households ' liabilities in financial institutions are dominated by consumer loans, which account for about two thirds of the residents ' liabilities and about two times that of operating loans.
Of these, around 80 per cent were medium- and long-term loans, mainly for housing, but, on an incremental basis, short-term consumer loans grew faster than medium- and long-term loans.
In addition, China ' s household debt rate is only a measure of the total amount of credit received by the household sector from financial institutions, while there are many private loans, including from relatives and friends, and large-scale hidden debts.
Seen in this way, there is some obfuscation. According to the Suning Institute of Finance, China ' s leverage rate was only 3 per cent in 1996 and 18 per cent in 2008, but since 2008 it has begun to grow rapidly, doubling to 36.4 per cent in just six years. By the third quarter of 2017, the rate had reached 48.6 per cent.
In another comparison, last May the HSBC Bank published a survey that spans nine countries and is close to 10,000 people.
The report is addressed to young people from nine countries (born between 1980 and 2000).
The report indicates that China ' s 80-90-year-old youth housing ownership is as high as 70 per cent and that it is the second-largest Mexican (46 per cent) and twice as high as the United States target (35 per cent).
These data tell us that there is a great potential problem, namely, that the largest potential “grey rhinoceros” in China at this stage may not be able to pay the debt, compared to the inability to afford housing.
Why is the housing debt crisis the most serious problem?
As we have previously analysed, although we have been saying that housing prices are high in China, the country's housing ownership rate is actually quite high compared to the rest of the world, so rather than the high cost of housing, I'm afraid the question for many friends now is whether you can afford a loan?
As we look at the world's real estate markets, China's real estate markets, due to their late start, have not experienced an excessive real estate crisis, except for what we said earlier in Hainan, but the origin of the world's financial tsunami of 2008 was the US real estate crisis just a decade ago.
The real estate crisis in the United States, on the other hand, was attributed to two houses: Remy and the United States.
In the golden age of the United States, when real estate companies sold their houses to the then low-income American population at very low downs in order to expand their sales, the real estate market was also booming when the United States economy was better, but the good news was that, with growth stagnating in the United States, it had led to lower incomes for home buyers, and a significant decline in household consumption spending began.
However, the current situation in the United States was that of a financial and real estate asset that formed part of United States household assets, with almost all household assets of low-income groups in the United States being real estate, while most of the assets of the top 20 per cent of the high-income groups were financial assets, resulting in higher debt ratios for the poorer households in the United States.
A serious fact is that these people buy houses when the economy is better, so the money paid for the mortgage is also calculated in terms of their better income. When the income falls, not only does the pressure on the mortgage not diminish, but even because some subprime schemes have increased, so the real estate problems of these American families have gradually become a real estate crisis.
As a result, the banks began to repossess the property because they were too low in income to pay for it, and after the banks had recovered the property from the buyer who had defaulted on the loan, they would sell it at very low prices, leading to a gradual decline in the region ' s housing prices, a process that led to a further decline in the price of the house, creating a vicious circle in which, when the house price fell to a certain extent, more and more buyers found their house to be even less valuable than their own loans, resulting in more people stopping to repay their mortgages and more bad debts.
As a result, a huge vicious circle emerged:
“The economic downturn — the decline in income — some people cannot afford to pay their mortgages — the low bank prices for the sale of the houses of the debtors — the fall in the house prices — more people stop paying their mortgages — the banks sell again — and the prices fall ”
The problem is more than that, because the price of the house continues to fall, it is not that you have no debt after people stop paying the house to the bank, and if the bank has not received the money you owe the bank, then you still need to pay back, simply assuming that you bought a house worth $3 million with a down payment of $600,000, $2.4 million with a down payment, and that when the house was worth only $2 million, you stopped paying the house to the bank, and after the bank auctioned the house, you not only lost your down payment of $600,000, but you owe the bank $400,000.
Thus, in such a vicious cycle, the United States economy gradually collapsed, culminating in the 2008 United States financial crisis.
Thus, at this stage, China’s high household debt rate of 46.8 per cent is a matter of great caution. This figure is still below that of the developed world, but the problem has begun to emerge, and the country has repeatedly emphasized the issue of deleveraging since last year. This is a very early judgement that if the household debt rate is allowed to continue rising, it will entail enormous risks, so that financial risks will be carefully prevented.
As a result, the country has accelerated the establishment of multi-subject supply, multi-channel security, lease-purchase and other measures to further address potential risks.
For our individual families, it is important to abandon speculative thinking about real estate and to buy a house as much as possible, so that their families do not fall into a huge burden. Only a reasonable assessment of their income and level of indebtedness is a healthy path to family wealth development.
